# Intro
# Hi everyone. As all the masters are not home, we finally got the chance to show our special skills. Today we are preparing a “special” spicy fish dish to satisfy a whole family of chili lovers.
# What’s so special about this dish? According to chef Jiao, it’s special when you have a lot of flavors going on. In other words, we need A LOT of ingredients for this dish.
# It’s quite easy to prepare. We use grass carp, which is commonly available. We need to wipe off the excess water after cleaning the fish (why?), then we will remove the bones (how) and the cut the fish into slices. Then we will marinate it for about 20 minutes with salt, ginger, spring onion, yellow Chinese rice wine, and starch.
# Then, we heat up the wok and pour some cold oil in. We even used some pork fat to intensify the aroma. Fry the spring onion, garlic and ginger in the wok with some Doubanjiang (Sichuan chili bean paste), some star anise, and nutmeg. Then, we put cloves, tsao-ko, dried mandarin peels, bay leaves, cinnamon, baizhi (Angelica dahurica) in and fry for a while, then we add chili pepper and water to cook for about 20 minutes on low heat. After 10 minutes we need to add chili flakes and Sichuan pepper.
# Why do we add them in the middle of the boiling process? To prevent the chili flakes to get burned, also to keep the numbing taste of the Sichuan pepper.
# Also, remember there are different types of Sichuan pepper and we use them for different purposes.
# Also, we will let you know why you should soak the chili peppers before frying tiem.
# Pay attention and learn about all the details in our video.
# This dish comes with a pleasant red color, features a spicy and numbing taste without being too overwhelming or bitter. It will surely satisfy your desire for spiciness. Get your gears going if you are feeling hungry!
# Maybe you do not have all those spices we used, that’s fine, just improvise a bit and use whatever you have in stock.

